T1  - Deviations from purchasing power parity: causes and welfare costs
AU  - Engel, Charles
AU  - Rogers, John H.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 55
IS  - 1
SP  - 29
EP  - 57
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01/
T2  - Intranational & International Economics
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(01)00094-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199601000940
KW  - Purchasing power parity
KW  - Fixed exchange rates
KW  - Law of one price
AB  - We explore deviations from short-run purchasing power parity (PPP) across European cities, attempting to move beyond a ‘first-generation’ of papers that document very large border effects. We document two very distinct types of border effects embedded in relative prices. The first is a ‘real barriers effect’, caused by various barriers to market integration. The second is a sticky-consumer-price cum volatile exchange-rate effect. Both are shown to be important empirically, the second type especially so. We argue that the two effects are very different from each other. For the first type of effect, it is clear that border effects imply deadweight welfare losses. We argue that while the second type of border effect could be eliminated with fixed exchange rates, welfare is not necessarily increased.
ER  - 

